note: CME seen to the northwest associated with an M4.9-class flare from AR 14001 which peaked at 2025-02-23T02:13Z at N25W82. note: Likely outflow associated with CME: 2025-02-23T02:36Z, an eruption associated with an M4.9-class flare from AR 14001 which peaked at 2025-02-23T02:13Z at N25W82. cmeAnalyses.note: Plane of sky measurement of the leading edge before it fades out of SOHO C2.

note: Very wide CME seen to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 during a STEREO A COR2A data gap composed with a well-defined western and southwestern leading edge and not-as-defined northern leading edge, associated with an X2.0-class flare and subsequent eruption from AR 14001 (N25W87) as evidenced by strong brightening in SDO AIA 131 and quickly separating field lines seen in SDO AIA 193, 171 and GOES SUVI 284.

cmeAnalyses.note: Shock front measurement using only SOHO imagery, encompassing the entire width of the CME in support of solar energetic particle modeling efforts. note: Very faint CME to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3. Not clearly seen in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source may be moving/opening field lines along the southern limb as seen in SDO/AIA 193 starting around 2025-02-24T00:12Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky parameters based on best fit using swpc_cat measuring technique and SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery.

At 2025-02-24T05:15Z, STEREO A was located 30.297 degrees from Earth, putting its west limb around W120.3. Here in STEREO A EUVI 304, the filament can be seen slowly rising starting at 2025-02-24T03:15Z->T5:15Z, and ejecting by the next timestamp at T05:45Z. A post-eruptive arcade follows in STEREO A EUVI 195/304. The source could be, or be near, old AR 3989, which rotated off the west limb on 2025-02-21 and would be located approximately W115-W125.

cmeAnalyses.note: BULK. Triangulated measurement of the brightest bulk portion of the leading edge, notably clipping some of the more faint nose off the northern portion in SOHO C3 imagery due to the uneven front. This analysis may be preliminary as further analysis continues.

This CME is very difficult to distinguish from the previous CME in white light imagery. The source is most likely associated with an M3.3 flare from AR 14000 (N17W21) that peaked at 2025-02-24T07:02Z. The flare and a region of dimming projected south of the flare are seen across SDO AIA and GOES SUVI wavelengths but are best seen in SDO AIA 193. There also appears to be some western deflection.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on running difference imagery from STEREO A COR2 and on-disk source location. This CME is very difficult to distinguish from the previous CME is C2 and is obscured by the pylon in C3.

note: Faint CME seen to the NNW in only SOHO LASCO C2, it fades quickly in the FOV after its initial visibility from the occulting disk. No source is observed for this front in EUV imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky in SOHO LASCO C2 only as it fades in the FOV.

note: This CME is first seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3, but not in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap beginning at 2025-02-24T20:23Z. Additionally, very fast opening field lines are visible from beyond the W limb starting around 2025-02-24T20:24Z in SDO/AIA 193, SDO/AIA 171, GOES SUVI 195, and GOES SUVI 284.

cmeAnalyses.note: This is a SHOCK measurement. Parameters based on best fit adjusted from source location using single-spacecraft measurement method. There is no STEREO A COR2 imagery available for this event due to a data gap.

Measurement based best fit in running difference imagery from SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and probable source location of M3.3 occulted flare from beyond the W limb.

note: Bright CME first seen in the SW by STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2025-02-25T12:38Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C2/C3 in later frames. cmeAnalyses.note: SOHO LASCO C2/C3 only plane-of-sky due to far-sided source with no STEREO COR2A imagery to triangulate with.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location. CME is too faint to be reliably tracked and triangulated in STEREO A COR2.

cmeAnalyses.note: POS measurement due to uncertain source location and lack of reliable STEREO A COR2 imagery for triangulation.

cmeAnalyses.note: Parameters based on best fit of brightest leading edge and bulk of CME.

cmeAnalyses.note: Parameters based on best fit of features in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 difference imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Parameters are based off of the best fit of the features in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on source location as well as the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery in SWPC_CAT.

Moving/opening field lines are also visible in SDO AIA 171/193 and dimming is visible in SDO AIA 193.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location using SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery in SWPC_CAT. STEREO A COR2 imagery was not available for this measurement.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.

The source of this event is a jet-like eruption from Active Region 4006 (N18W02), exhibiting a very strong Northeastern deflection in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2.

This is also confirmed by the fact that the EUV wave is not seen on the Earth facing side in EUV imagery, but there are signatures of a far-sided EUV wave behind the limb, seen in AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284 imagery.

note: CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-28T16:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. This CME partially overlaps and is obscured by CME: 2025-02-28T17:12Z in later frames.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.

note: This CME is visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery with a very bright core mostly on the right side of the CME. The source is a large L-shaped filament eruption stretching from ~S35W10 to ~S15E40 centered around ~S35E20 starting around 2025-03-01T17:00Z. Brightening is visible in SDO/AIA, GOES SUVI, and STEREO A EUVI 304. Dimming, moving/opening field lines, and post-eruptive arcades are best visible in GOES SUVI 284 and SDO/AIA 193.

cmeAnalyses.note: Parameters based on best fit adjusted from source location with apparent deflection to the south taken into account.

note: This CME is visible in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery to the S/SE in the outflow of the previous CME starting at 2025-03-01T18:24Z. A well defined loop with filament ejecta in the middle is seen lifting from the source region with clear moving/opening field lines and EUV wave to the south starting around 2025-03-01T23:00Z. There appears to be strong deflection to the south with this event as evident by the moving/opening field lines in GOES SUVI 284 imagery.

These parameters are based on following the faster portion of the CME with including the slower portion within the width of the measurement. The slower portion of this CME was measuring speeds closer to 200 km/s.

note: Faintest of the 3 consecutive narrow jets from AR 4011 this morning. Its source is likely the C1.2 flare from AR 4011 (S18E57) starting at 2025-03-02T05:46Z.

note: Faint narrow CME to the southeast in both coronagraphs, best seen in running difference imagery. cmeAnalyses.note: Analysis based on the best fit with two coronagraphs. Faint coronal signatures also indicate that this is a far-sided CME.

cmeAnalyses.note: Parameters based on best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

Preliminary measurement based on the approximate source location.

S20-S25 and E110-E90) starting at about 2025-03-05T03:34Z in SDO AIA 171 imagery. Post-eruptive arcades appear several hours later and seemingly from the same location starting at about 2025-03-05T06:36Z in SDO AIA 171.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement using the location of the source seen in UV imagery of the Earth-facing disk and the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2. The full leading edge and a small interior flux rope are both faintly visible in C2, but this CME is only tentatively seen as an extremely faint feature for two frames in STEREO A COR2, so there is some uncertainty with this measurement. The best fit parameters match well with the approximated source location if taking into account some southern deflection, though, which increases confidence a bit. Leading edge is too diffuse to track in SOHO LASCO C3.
Plane-of-sky measurement using several frames of SOHO LASCO C2 imagery. Leading edge is too diffuse to track in SOHO LASCO C3.

note: CME seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, and briefly in STEREO COR2A before a data gap begins at 2025-03-05T11:53Z. The source is a small filament which spanned roughly N28W55->N28W70 (centered N28W62) near AR 14006 (N18W70) at 2025-03-05T10:09Z just before erupting. The eruption is best seen in SDO AIA 304 as the filament material brightening and lifting off, and also observed in SDO AIA 171 as field line movement to the NW.

cmeAnalyses.note: Triangulated measurement using mostly SOHO LASCO C2/C3 frames, with two STEREO COR2A frames helping triangulate the longitude prior to its data gap beginning at 2025-03-05T11:53Z. This CME front diffuses out after an initial solid view in LASCO C2, it was much easier to track the leading edge in the earliest frames used for this measurement.

note: A CME seen north in both coronagraphs and following the path of the 2025-03-05T11:00Z CME.  Its likely source is a minor eruption with minor dimming and jagged ejecta seen in the NE at 2025-03-05T18:18Z in AIA 171 (N32W55), followed by the minor post-eruptive arcades.

cmeAnalyses.note: Analysis based on the best fit with two coronagraphs. There seems to be a northward and eastward deflection from the location of the source eruption.

note: Narrow and faint jet CME visible to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Source is a faint and narrow loop / opening field line movement can be seen in GOES SUVI 284 off the NE limb, first distinguishable at 2025-03-06T03:00Z when the loop is already near the edge of the SUVI 284 field of view. There are two candidates for the origin of this loop: 1) a very small instance of brightening at 2025-03-06T02:58Z from AR 4017 (S05E56), or 2) from just beyond the NE limb, likely located near the northernmost footpoint of the arc of field lines visible on the NE limb in UV imagery which turns into the streamer visible to the NE in coronagraph imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Best fit measurement using several frames of SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2. Narrow leading edge is faint but well-defined in C2, distinguishable but not as well-defined in STEREO A COR2, and defined for only two frames in C3.

note: Faint loop CME visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2. Source is an area of dimming and opening field lines seen from AR 4016 (S26E33) and the surrounding area, which spans from S10 to S30 and E30 to E40, starting at 2025-03-06T04:39Z in SDO AIA 193. The opening field lines appear to be deflected southward and westward in SDO AIA 193/171.

cmeAnalyses.note: Best fit measurement using several frames of SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2. Leading edge is too diffuse to reliably track in SOHO LASCO C3. This best-fit measurement corroborates the southward and westward deflection of this eruption from the source location as was suspected based on visual inspection of UV imagery.

note: Bright CME first seen to the SSE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-03-07T02:00Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event in an eruption centered at approx. S30E10 beginning at approx. 07/01:15Z as seen in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304. Dimming is also visible in SDO AIA 193 exhibiting a strong Southern deflection. A larger coronal hole is visible to the North of this eruption sight in SDO AIA 211, which may be contributing to the Southern deflection.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.

note: CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-03-07T02:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a filament eruption seen in the SW by SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304 beginning at approx. 07/01:28Z centered at approx. S40W90 with Southern deflection.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3.

note: Faint CME first seen in the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-03-07T03:12Z. This CME fades before exiting the FOV in C2 and is therefore not visible in SOHO LASCO C3 or STEREO A COR2. The source of this event is a minor eruption seen along the SE limb in SDO AIA 304 beginning at approx. 07/02:45Z, along with faint field line opening seen in SDO AIA 193.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement due to source location near the limb and lack of reliable STEREO A COR2 imagery.

note: Faint CME first seen to the East by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-03-07T09:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this event is some minor field line movement seen along the Eastern limb in SDO AIA 171.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.

note: CME first seen in the NW by SOHO LASCO C2. The source of this event is an area of field line opening seen along or just beyond the NW limb in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284. Post eruptive arcades are also visible in SDO AIA 94 and 131 following the opening. This CME is almost entirely obstructed by a data gap in STEREO A COR2 which lasted from 2025-03-07T14:53Z to 2025-03-07T21:23Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement tracking the northernmost feature (as seen in SOHO LASCO C2), which seems to correspond to an extremely faint loop seen in late frames of STEREO A COR2. This feature in C2 appears to be traveling slightly faster than the surrounding/overlapping material, which becomes diffuse and seems to fall apart or loose momentum before reaching the edge of the C2 field of view. The northernmost feature reaches into the SOHO LASCO C3 field of view.

note: CME seen to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2 and in later STEREO A COR2 frames. Source is a filament close to the SW limb (spans S35W60 to S30W90) seen lifting off starting at 2025-03-07T18:45Z in SDO AIA 171, 193, and 304. Bright ejecta can be seen off the SW limb in SDO AIA 171 and 304, and in GOES SUVI 304 a large loop of ejected filamentary material can be seen by 2025-03-07T19:20Z, which fully departs the GOES SUVI field of view by about 2025-03-07T20:36Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.

note: Loop CME seen to the SW in both SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Source is an M1.6 flare and eruption from AR 4016 (S26E10). Dimming with southward deflection is seen starting at 2025-03-07T20:59Z in SDO AIA 193 and spans about 10 degrees radially around AR 4016 i.e. from S15 to S35 and from E20 to E00. Opening field lines with some southward deflection can be seen in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284 as well. Post-eruptive brightening can be seen in SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 304, including some from nearby AR 4012 (S13W06) starting at 2025-03-07T21:04Z. An EUV wave is seen propagating southward from AR 4016 in SDO AIA 193.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement using best fit between the abundance of SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 frames available. Source location with southern deflection observed in UV imagery was taken into consideration when conducting this measurement.

note: This narrow on-disk CME is seen as a faint flux rope due south in SOHO LASCO C2 and simultaneously as a faint loop to the southeast in STEREO A COR2, which is currently 30 degrees to the west of SOHO LASCO. The source is a subtle eruption from AR 4012 (S20W00) starting at 2025-03-07T21:35Z, seen as dimming, brightening, and field line opening in SDO AIA 193 and 171, as well as GOES SUVI 284 and 304.

cmeAnalyses.note: Best fit measurement using several frames of STEREO A COR2, four frames of SOHO LASCO C3, and two frames of SOHO LASCO C2. The leading edge is very faint in SOHO LASCO imagery; it is much more well-defined in STEREO A COR2. This CME visually overlaps with CME:2025-03-07T21:49Z in both SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2.

note: Relatively slow, diffuse CME seen to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2. Source is an eruption seen close to the SW limb as evidenced by moving field lines seen lifting off starting as early as 2025-03-08T06:08Z best in GOES SUVI 284. The signature is also seen well by opening magnetic field lines in SDO AIA 171 and 193.

cmeAnalyses.note: Leading edge of the southwest portion of the CME and not the leading edge seen more to the south in STEREO A COR2 later frames.

note: Narrow and fast CME seen to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery associated with a point source eruption from Active Region 14011 (S14W29) seen erupting around 2025-03-08T14:45Z in SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 284. The active region footpoint is seen to have a small brightening during the eruption followed by a dark jet of plasma material leaving to the southwest with some deflection to the west.

cmeAnalyses.note: Leading edge measurement using only SOHO C2 as the CME is not seen well in STEREO A, possibly being edge on. This measurement assumes some modest deflection of a few degrees to the west.

note: Faint, narrow, somewhat asymmetrical CME to the northeast, with a protruding pointy nose. Source: minor eruption/prominence on/behind the northeast limb seen in SDO AIA 304 at 2025-03-08T22:10Z and as very minor movement of field lines behind the NE limb in SDO AIA 171.

cmeAnalyses.note: At the time of analysis no STEREO A COR2 imagery is available because of the nighttime data gap. The source is likely behind the NE limb (possibly on the limb). No definitive 3D analysis is possible at the time, so only plane-of-sky measurement is performed.

note: This CME is visible to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. It is not observed in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting at 2025-03-09T11:53Z. The source is likely related to an eruption, which exhibits northern deflection, visible on or slightly beyond the northeast limb (~N30E90) starting around 2025-03-03T12:25Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measured longitude based on the approximate source location.

note: This event is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and south in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely related to an eruption from Active Region 14012 (S15W40) starting around 2025-03-10T03:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. The source eruption exhibits a southeast deflection, suggesting that the CME parameters may measure southeast of the on-disk source location.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the approximate source location, accounting for southeast deflection, and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 coronagraphs.

note: This event is visible to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely related to an eruption visible on or slightly beyond the northeast limb starting around 2025-03-10T05:25Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

note: This CME is visible to the south/southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and to the south in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source may be related to a minor eruption near Active Region 14016 (~S25W25) starting around 2025-03-10T08:30Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. Dimming is observed in SDO AIA 193 at this time as well.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the approximate source location, accounting for southern deflection, and the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

note: This CME is faint but visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. It is too faint to observe in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided and may be related to faint field-line movement visible over the southwest limb starting around 2025-03-10T10:25Z as seen in SDO AIA 171 imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: A plane-of-sky measurement was made using a longitude of 90 degrees. A triangulated measurement was not available as this CME is undetectable in STEREO A COR2 imagery.

note: This CME is faint but visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery before the leading edge becomes too diffuse to observe. The source is likely far-sided as there are no source signatures on the Earth-facing disk at the time of this event.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

note: Faint and relatively narrow CME to the southwest in STEREO A COR2 and SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. The leading edge appears slightly brighter in STEREO A COR2 than in SOHO LASCO. The source is opening field lines seen starting at 2025-03-11T03:35Z located on or just beyond the W limb as seen in STEREO A EUVI 195 (W120-130 from SDO AIA perspective) and spanning approximately N00 to S10 in latitude, although the eruption likely extends to farther beyond the limb. Field line movement and the disappearance of a small loop of material can be seen from the same location in STEREO A EUVI 304 imagery between the 2025-03-11T03:45Z and 2025-03-11T04:45Z frames.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement using source location seen in UV imagery and best fit between a few frames of SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 running difference imagery. The leading edge is very faint in both coronagraphs and becomes too diffuse to reliably track about halfway through the SOHO LASCO C3 field of view.

note: Super narrow jet (with the 2 degree half-width or so), seen only in SOHO LASCO C2 and faintly in a few early timestamps of C3. Not discernible in STEREO A COR2, likely because of its faintness. Likely associated with the M1.1 flare from AR 14024 (N5W47).

cmeAnalyses.note: Very approximate analysis as this jet was measured with the 10 deg halfwidth using the one-coronagraph method in swpc_cat, based only on SOHO imagery and on the location of the associated flare. While the jet is extremely narrow (<2 degrees half-width, lowest half-width setting in swpc_cat that we have to use is 10 degrees).

note: Narrow, relatively fast CME seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery and more directed towards the north in STEREO Ahead COR2 imagery composed of a fainter, faster shock. No sources on the Earth-facing disk in EUV imagery seem to be associated with this event, so the CME is likely associated with far-sided eruptive activity.

cmeAnalyses.note: Leading edge measurement using triangulation from two spacecraft (SOHO, STEREO A) to determine a potential longitude; approximately a 20 degree uncertainty in longitude.

note: Narrow CME seen to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2 during a COR2A data gap. Appears to be associated with a minor eruption from Active Region 14024 (N07W57) and C9.6-class flare as evidenced by dimming seen in SDO AIA 193 and GOES SUVI 294 starting around 2025-03-11T21:28Z as well as brightening visible in SDO AIA 131.

cmeAnalyses.note: Leading edge measurement using only SOHO imagery and knowledge of the source eruption location to determine the longitude.

note: Narrow, relatively fast CME seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery and not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap; it appears similar in appearance to the CME: 2025-03-11T18:24Z which was determined to likely be far-sided. Few, if any sources on the Earth-facing disk suggest that this CME occurs with eruptive activity on the Earth-facing disk.

cmeAnalyses.note: SOHO plane of sky measurement as STEREO A COR2 data is not available at the time of the eruption.

note: Bulbous jet-like CME to northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and to the north in STEREO, similar to the 2025-03-11T23:24Z CME. No clear source was found on disk but there are some movements of field lines behind the limb in the NE after 05Z in AIA 193. The CME is likely farsided.

cmeAnalyses.note: Analysis based solely on the fit with two coronagraphs.

note: A super faint jet to the northwest, seen mostly in SOHO LASCO C2 and in a few early timestamps of C3 and too faint to be seen in STEREO A COR2. There is no flare that can be associated with it but there is some brightening in AR 14024 after 2025-03-12T06Z seen in SDO AIA 193 and it is possibly associated with activity in this Active Region.

cmeAnalyses.note: No clear source found on disk and no STEREO A COR2 imagery available for this faint event, so only plane-of-sky measurement is definitive.

note: Super faint and narrow jet only seen in SOHO LASCO C2 running difference imagery and in a few early C3 images and not seen in STEREO A COR2. No source has been found for this jet.

cmeAnalyses.note: Super faint and narrow jet only seen in SOHO LASCO C2 running difference imagery and in a few early C3 images and not seen in STEREO A COR2. No source has been found for this jet.

note: CME first seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2 white light imagery starting at 2025-03-12T20:04Z. Also seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO C3 but is not seen in STEREO A COR2. This jet may have been visible in running difference imagery shortly before it was visible in white light imagery and has a half-width of less than ten degrees. There is not a good source candidate on the Earth-facing disk; however, there are some possible post eruptive arcades on or just beyond the NE limb (approximately N35-N40) best seen in SDO AIA 171 beginning around 2025-03-12T21:15Z that could be related to this jet.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement made with running difference imagery from SOHO LASCO C2/C3. A plane-of-sky measurement was chosen due to the lack of certainty in a source location.

note: Faint CME seen to the SSE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A. The source may be field line movement in SDO AIA 171 observed over the SSW limb beginning around 2025-03-12T23:18Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Difficult to triangulate measurement between SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO COR2A due to the faint, wispy nature of the leading edge. Good confidence in the high southern latitude and longitude around W50-W60.

note: Faint CME seen to the ESE in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO COR2A for a few frames before it fades, never reaching LASCO C3 imagery. First seen more clearly in SOHO LASCO C2 running difference imagery at 2025-03-13T03:48Z. The source for this CME is likely field line movement in SDO AIA 171 on or just inside the SE limb starting around 2025-03-13T02:53Z, from the northern side of AR 14028.

cmeAnalyses.note: Triangulated measurement between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO COR2A, using only the earliest frames as the CME fades into the running difference background by 2025-03-13T06:00Z.

note: CME seen to the SW in STEREO COR2A only, as SOHO LASCO C2/C3 is in a data gap from 2025-03-13T07:30Z -> 2025-03-13T22:10Z. No source for this CME is observed in SDO AIA or STEREO A EUVI imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: STEREO A plane-of-sky measurement as no SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery is available. At the CME start time STEREO A is located 30.981 degrees west of Earth, putting its western plane-of-sky around W121 relative to Earth.

note: CME seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 composed of a bright narrow bulk and a fainter shock extending to the north and west relative to the bulk. The source is a minor eruption from near Active Region 4020 (N20E13) with northern deflection as seen in SDO AIA 193, 171, 304 as early as 2025-03-13T16:49Z; darkening in SDO AIA 193, brightening in SDO AIA 304 and the appearance of a breaking loop in SDO AIA 171.

cmeAnalyses.note: One spacecraft measurement (SOHO) of the leading edge assuming some modest northern deflection and fitting relative to the source observed in EUV imagery.

Measurement of wider shock front using only SOHO C2 and knowledge of the source as determined from EUV imagery. Attached WSA-Enlil+Cone simulation was executed in support of SEP models and should not be used for CME trajectory analysis. Based on simulation output, there is low confidence the CME may arrive at Earth very weakly.

note: CME seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 and east-northeast in STEREO A COR2A composed of a bright narrow bulk extending to the northeast and second more minor outflow seen more to the north. The source may be associated with a minor eruption seen near the eastern limb around E80 as early as 2025-03-14T02:00Z; mostly in GOES SUVI 284 imagery, or the eruption may be far-sided.

cmeAnalyses.note: Two spacecraft leading edge measurement in order to triangulate a possible longitude; uncertainty in longitude up to +/- 20 degrees.

note: CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-03-14T15:25Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap beginning at 14/15:53Z. The source of this event is a minor eruption from AR 4022 (N08E11) beginning at approx. 14/14:28Z. Dimming seen in SDO AIA 193 and 211 suggest a strong Eastern deflection.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2. This event is measuring slightly more narrow than the SWPC_CAT lower limit of 10 degrees.

note: An extremely narrow faint jet seen mostly in running difference imagery in SOHO and STEREO A to the northeast. No clear source has been found in the EUV imagery at the time but there is a super minor ejecta in SDO AIA 304 at 01:40Z on the NE limb which may be related.

cmeAnalyses.note: Approximate analysis based solely on the fit with two coronagraphs.

note: One of two overlapping loop CMEs visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2. The source is additional wide and subtle field line movement seen on and very likely extending beyond the SW limb, best seen in STEREO A EUVI 193, and likely a direct consequence of or sympathetic eruption to a filament eruption seen starting at to lift off the southwest limb at 2025-03-15T04:09Z as seen in SDO AIA 304, 193, and 171. This CME heavily overlaps with CME: 2025-03-15T05:36Z, whose source is the filament eruption on the southwest limb.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement made using the best fit between abundant frames of SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 running difference imagery, as well as consideration of the source location seen in available STEREO A EUV, SDO AIA, and GOES SUVI imagery.

note:
One of two overlapping loop CMEs visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2. The source is a filament eruption on the southwest limb, spanning from about S25W85 to S10W120 with southward deflection seen as it erupts in SDO AIA and STEREO-A EUV imagery. This CME heavily overlaps with CME: 2025-03-15T05:24Z, whose source is nearly simultaneous and in close proximity. 

Filamentary material is seen starting to lift off at 2025-03-15T04:09Z in SDO AIA 304, 193, and 171. Post-eruptive arcades can be seen in SDO AIA 193 and 171 starting at 2025-03-15T06:28Z and lasting for multiple hours. Bright material can be seen in GOES SUVI 304 as well. This eruption is also visible in STEREO A EUVI 304 and 193 imagery, which has frames available after a data gap ending at 2025-03-15T03:45Z and reveals liftoff of material starting with the next frame with timestamp 2025-03-15T04:15Z. With STEREO A currently at a HEEQ longitude of 31, this vantage point reveals that there was a filament eruption and a separate but sympathetic rising loop directly next to the filament, which altogether extended from approximately S25W80 to S10W121 (coordinates listed as would be seen by SDO. STEREO A is currently at a HEEQ longitude of +31 degrees).

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement made using the best fit between abundant frames of SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 running difference imagery, as well as consideration of the source location seen in available STEREO A EUV, SDO AIA, and GOES SUVI imagery.

note: Narrow faint jet seen to the northeast in a couple of early timestamps in SOHO LASCO C2. Not seen in STEREO A COR2. A possible source is a narrow bright ejecta on/behind the east limb in AIA 304 around 2025-03-15T18:30Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: The possible source (ejecta) is seen on/behind the east limb in SDO AIA 304. The CME is not seen in STEREO A COR2 coronagraph. Only plane-of-sky analysis is definitive.

note: Complex-shaped, somewhat pointy-nosed and possibly partial halo CME to the southwest, seen the brightest in STEREO A COR2. Its source is behind the SW limb (both in SDO and in STEREO A) and likely associated with Active Region 4012 (now at approximately W125) which was fairly complex when it was on the Earth-facing disk; its coronal signatures are fast-opening field lines behind the SW limb in both EUV imagers starting at 2025-03-16T00:32Z, as seen in SDO AIA 193/171, EUVI A 195 and SUVI 285. Much later (after 05Z) some high post-eruptive arcades are seen in EUVI A 304 appearing from behind the limb, indicating the source that is far behind the limb, as seen from STEREO A. The much fainter shock can be best seen mostly as it pushes the streamer in the south south west towards the east. Likely deflection of about 10 to 20 degrees eastward relative to the source at W125 caused by a large coronal hole located to the northwest of Active Region 4012.

cmeAnalyses.note: Uncertain analysis based solely on the best possible fit with two coronagraphs. The high posts-eruptive arcades behind the west limb in STEREO A EUV imagery showing much later than the original coronal signatures of opening field lines indicate the source with the longitude >120 deg. However, no fit was found with longitudes >115 deg and the best fit was obtained with the longitude of 109 degrees. Likely deflection of about 10 to 20 degrees eastward relative to the source at W125 would be caused by a large coronal hole located to the northwest of Active Region 4012 at approximately W125.

note: Narrow jet/outflow seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO and in 2 timestamps surrounding a data gap in STEREO A COR2. No clear source was found on disk.

cmeAnalyses.note: A very uncertain analysis based on the fit of the very faint fuzzy front in both coronagraphs. No source has been found.

note: Minor faint and narrow CME best seen to the east in SOHO LASCO C2 and in a couple of early timestamps of C3 and fully covered by a data gap in STEREO A COR2. No clear source was found on disk.

cmeAnalyses.note: The CME is covered by a data gap in STEREO A COR2. No clear source was found on disk. Only plane-of-sky measurement is definitive.

note: An extremely faint fuzzy CME/outflow/possible partial halo to the north-northwest, seen in SOHO LASCO C2 and even more faintly for a few early timestamps in C3, but not seen in STEREO A COR2, likely because of faintness. Better seen in running difference imagery. Its source is most likely the medium-size but pretty faint dimming seen starting ~2025-03-16T10:09Z, signifying eruption to the northwest of Active Region 4023 and centered (~N20W10), seen in SDO AIA 193 and GOES SUVI 284.

cmeAnalyses.note: One-coronagraph analysis with corrected latitude of the CME (~25 degrees). Analysis is based on SOHO imagery and on the location of the likely source - faint eruption centered around (N25W10).

note: Partial halo CME with bulk seen to the north-northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery and more towards the northeast in STEREO A COR2 imagery with faint, very wide shock developing in later frames with invisible leading edge containing lobes to the north and east in both SOHO and STEREO A imagery. The presumed source is an eruption from near the vicinity of Active Region 4032 (N35E35) seen as a dimming in SDO AIA 193 as early as 2025-03-16T18:04Z, disappearing loop structure in SDO AIA 171, and brightening in SDO AIA 304. There are two eruptions seen in GOES SUVI 304 imagery emanating from the same area, one seen at 18:49Z and another which appears more Earth-directed at 20:49Z. Triangulation using SOHO and STEREO A imagery seems to more strongly support Earth-directedness and deflection westward than the EUV imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement of the leading edge/bulk using two spacecraft out to 8 solar radii which supports westward deflection. Triangulation does not support the source location being near the original source location N35E35. Not yet seen in SOHO C3.

Very low confidence two spacecraft measurement of very faint shock front, which is hardly seen in running difference imagery. Attached WSA-ENLIL+Cone simulation was executed in support of SEP models and should not be used for CME trajectory analysis, potentially representing an overestimate of potential impacts relative to observations.

note: Very slow CME that looks like a slow streamer blowout, with a succession of almost identical faint fronts seen in both coronagraphs. The CME seems to accelerate, as seen in SOHO LASCO C3 imagery. There is no clear source seen on the disk, although there is a super minor dimming in AIA 193 centered around N30E10 starting after 00:30Z and continuing until 05Z, but it is extremely faint.

cmeAnalyses.note: Analysis made with later SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery, leaving C2 imagery out to account for clear acceleration of the CME (from <200 km/s to >400 km/s) in later imagery. Analysis is based on the best fit in two coronagraphs, as no clear source was found on disk.  Analysis incorporates a very faint left hand side boundary of this CME as seen in later COR2 imagery.

note: Faint CME first seen to the S in SOHO LASCO C2. Also seen to the S in STEREO A COR2 but is not seen in SOHO LASCO C3. A possible source candidate is a very small eruption far to the SE (~S60E10) best seen in GOES SUVI 284 starting about 2025-03-17T08:07Z; measurements align well with this possible source candidate.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 and a source candidate.

note: Faint CME first seen to the west in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-03-17T11:36Z. Also seen to the west in SOHO LASCO C3 but not visible in STEREO A COR2A imagery (where it would be near center disk from the perspective of STEREO A). The source of this CME is likely a small filament eruption centered around N12W30 which starts around 2025-03-17T10:36Z and is best seen in SDO AIA 304.

cmeAnalyses.note: Approximate one-coronagraph analysis with SOHO imagery only since the CME is not in STEREO A COR2A imagery (where it would be near center disk from the perspective of STEREO A). Analysis is based on the assumption that the source of this CME is a small filament eruption centered around N12W30 which starts around 2025-03-17T10:36Z and is best seen in SDO AIA 304.

note: Faint CME seen mostly in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 but with front not well seen in C3. The source of this CME is unclear. While there are some opening field lines visible on/beyond the east limb starting around 2025-03-17T10:54Z best seen in SDO AIA 171 and SDO AIA 193, the fit with two coronagraphs indicates a lower longitude for the source.

cmeAnalyses.note: Very approximate analysis based on the best fit with two coronagraphs, C2 and COR2A imagery only. The CME is too faint in C3. No clear source has been found for this CME.

note: Narrow pointy-nosed CME/outflow to the north, following preceding CMEs. No clear source has been found for it on disk.

cmeAnalyses.note: Approximate analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs. No source was found for this CME.

note: Bright loop CME first seen in the North by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-03-17T19:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 17/18:23Z to 18/03:09Z. The source of this event is a double peaked C9.8 and M1.0 flare from AR AR 4033 (N25E40) peaking at 2025-03-17T19:19Z and 2025-03-17T19:33Z respectively. This flare is visible in SDO AIA 131, along with field line opening seen in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284. This eruption also seems to have a footpoint slightly further to the West at approx. N30E05, evidenced by dimming seen in SDO AIA 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284. The field line loops appear to break off in stages, resulting in a second overlapping CME, CME: 2025-03-17T20:12Z. Both CMEs appear to exhibit a strong Northern deflection.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3

note: Bright, narrow CME first seen in the North by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-03-17T20:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 17/18:23Z to 18/03:09Z. The source of this event is a double peaked C9.8 and M1.0 flare from AR 4033 (N25E40) peaking at 2025-03-17T19:19Z and 2025-03-17T19:33Z respectively. This flare is visible in SDO AIA 131, along with field line opening seen in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284. This eruption also seems to have a footpoint slightly further to the West at approx. N30E05, evidenced by dimming seen in SDO AIA 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284. The field line loops appear to break off in stages, resulting in an earlier overlapping CME, CME: 2025-03-17T19:48Z. Both CMEs appear to exhibit a strong Northern deflection.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3

note: Faint, outflow-like CME first seen in the North by SOHO LASCO C2 at 2025-03-18T03:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The likely source of this event is continued dimming and field line movement following the C9.8 and M1.0 double peaked flare at 2025-03-17T19:04Z and 2025-03-17T19:25Z respectively.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate center of source dimming region and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2.

note: Faint, outflow-like CME first seen in the North by SOHO LASCO C2 at 2025-03-18T06:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The likely source of this event is continued dimming and field line movement following the C9.8 and M1.1 double peaked flare at 2025-03-17T19:04Z and 2025-03-17T19:25Z respectively.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate center of source dimming region and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3.

note: CME first seen in the East by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-03-18T08:36Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a filament eruption seen at approx. S30E65 in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304. Field line opening is also visible in SDO AIA 171 and 193, along with post eruptive arcades seen in SDO AIA 94, 131 and 193.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. This CME appears wider in COR2A likely due to the angle of the filament that each spacecraft is viewing.

note: This CME is visible to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery and is not observed in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting at 2025-03-18T15:39Z. The source is likely related to an opening of field lines visible beyond the northeast limb starting around 2025-03-18T15:30Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, and 193 imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: A plane-of-sky measurement was made using a longitude of -90 degrees due to the far-sided and therefore unknown source location.

note: This CME is faintly visible to the E/NE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. It is not clearly seen in STEREO A COR2 data due to a data gap from 2025-03-18T15:39Z to 2025-03-19T03:09Z. The source appears to be a filament eruption beyond the E/NE limb starting around 2025-03-19T00:30Z as seen in SDO/AIA 131, 171, 193, and 304.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement using SWPC_CAT analysis method using SOHO LASCO C3 frames.

note: Bright streamer blowout CME to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The CME is visibly wider in STEREO A COR2 imagery than in SOHO imagery. The source of this CME appears to be a complex series of eruptions beginning with an eruption near N05E05 starting around 2025-03-19T00:39Z. This eruption may have triggered additional instability of nearby magnetic field line foot points, which may be associated with the streamer itself. Dimming is clearly seen to the east of the initial eruption location starting around 2025-03-19T06:00Z. It is also around this time that the CME appears to begin to speed up in the SOHO field of view with a more clear/defined front appearing around this time as well.

cmeAnalyses.note: Parameters based on the best fit using SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

note: Faint and wide loop CME visible to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. Source is a filament eruption on or just beyond the NW limb in STEREO A EUVI 304 imagery, likely placing it at a longitude between W120 to W130, and spanning from approximately N10 to N40, with liftoff of filamentary material seen starting at 2025-03-19T03:45Z. Simultaneous opening field line movement can also be seen in STEREO A EUVI 304 imagery, centered at N50, just to the north of the filament eruption, and possibly located further beyond the limb than the filament due to the faintness of this signature. A second, smaller loop of material centered at about N40 can be seen lifting off at 2025-03-19T06:15Z in STEREO A EUVI 304 which may be the source of the additional outflow seen in coronagraph imagery following this CME. Field line movement can also be seen on or beyond the NW limb in STEREO A EUVI 195. The quality and cadence of STEREO A COR2 imagery was affected during time of analysis due to a campaign scheduled to last from 2025-03-18 to 2025-03-24.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement using best fit between SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery, as well as the approximated location of the source seen in STEREO A EUV imagery. The quality and cadence of STEREO A COR2 imagery was affected during time of analysis due to a campaign scheduled to last from 2025-03-18 to 2025-03-24.

note: Faint but fast CME with an asymmetrical front, with a protruding nose to the south, seen directed to the west in SOHO with the start covered by the nighttime data gap in SOHO. Its source is the filament eruption seen on/behind the SW limb: as ejecta/prominence in AIA 304 (there are actually two ejectas - a more southern complex shaped loop-like prominence seen at 2025-03-19T22:50Z at latitude of -21, and a fan-shaped ejecta to the north of it seen at latitude of -7 at 2025-03-19T223:46Z. This eruption is also seen as fast opening of field lines behind the limb in AIA 193/171 starting at 2025-03-19T222:01Z and later (starting at 2025-03-19T223:21Z) as bright post-eruptive arcades on/behind the limb in AIA 131. There is an associated long duration occulted C6.0 flare peaking at 2025-03-20T00:07Z from behind the limb (bright arcades). It is possible that the flare is from former Active Region 4018 (S21W100).

cmeAnalyses.note: Updated measurement using the approximated source longitude of former Active Region 14018, which was estimated to be centered near west 100 degrees at the time of this event. The measured parameters may vary slightly due to a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery.

Since the source is on or behind the limb and STEREO A coronagraph imagery is not yet available because of the nighttime data gap, only a plane-of-sky analysis is possible at this time (although the CME is likely close to the limb and this plane-of-sky measurement may be close to the 3D one).

note: Faint loop CME visible to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, with a faint flux rope feature more visible in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is the ejection of material from just beyond the southwest limb, first distinctly seen as a distinct instance of opening field lines and ejecta starting around 2025-03-19T23:15Z in GOES SUVI 304 and 284 imagery. Post-eruptive brightening extends onto the disk spanning from about S10 to S15 and W80 to W90, as seen in SDO AIA 304 at 2025-03-19T23:40Z. Associated surrounding field line movement extends into the northern hemisphere on or beyond the western limb, and some northern deflection occurs as the material erupts.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement using best fit between SOHO LASCO C3 running difference and STEREO A COR2 difference imagery, as well as the approximated location of source seen in available UV imagery of the Earth-facing disk. The quality and cadence of STEREO A COR2 imagery was affected during time of analysis due to a campaign scheduled to last from 2025-03-18 to 2025-03-24.

note: Loop CME with brighter, narrower bulk and fainter shock visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 during a STEREO A COR2 data gap. The source of the CME appears to the ejection of material from near the vicinity of Active Region 4022 just near N08W75, first distinctly seen as a distinct instance of opening field lines and brightening starting around 2025-03-20T17:24Z in SDO AIA 193 and 304 imagery. Faint flickering field lines far off the western limb seen in GOES SUVI 284 suggest that a component of this large scale eruption may be far-sided.

cmeAnalyses.note: Leading edge measurement using one spacecraft assuming the source is associated with an eruption just north of AR 4022.

note: Faint CME seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A. This CME is slow to evolve and appear as a defined front in the LASCO C2 field-of-view, and appears more clear in LASCO C3 and STEREO COR2A. The source for this CME is not observed as a distinct source, but appears to be continued outflow from CME 2025-03-20T17:12Z from AR 14022 centered at N08W75, corroborated via triangulation in the STEREO_CAT tool.

cmeAnalyses.note: StereoCAT measurement using SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO COR2A due to unusable data quality of COR2A running difference imagery in the swpc_cat tool, due to an ongoing STEREO A campaign.

note: Faint CME seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, and to the S in two available frames of STEREO COR2A before a data gap begins at 2025-03-21T15:09Z. No source for this CME is observed in SDO and GOES imagery, suggesting a far-sided source alongside comparison between the CME direction in white light SOHO LASCO and STEREO COR2A imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: SOHO LASCO C2/C3 only plane-of-sky measurement as available STEREO COR2A running difference imagery quality cannot discern the CME due to an ongoing campaign.

note: Faint halo CME with a bulk visible mainly to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery (more easily seen in difference imagery). There is no STEREO A COR2 imagery for this event due to a data gap. The source of this CME appears to be a large dimming region centered near N02E07 starting around 2025-03-21T15:49Z with a southeast directionality based on the minor EUV wave visible in SDO/AIA 211 and 193 imagery. There's a large coronal hole situated E/SE of the dimming region and a separate coronal hole due west of the dimming region which may have contributed to the deflection visible on the solar disk in SDO/AIA imagery. This source location appears to be a sympathetic eruption to the M1.2 flare from AR14028 (S17W33) seen to the SW in SDO/AIA 131 imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Parameters based on the SHOCK of the CME using SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. High uncertainty due to lack of stereoscopic viewpoints.

Parameters based on the BULK of the CME using SOHO LASCO C2 imagery. The front of the bulk is not clearly visible in SOHO LASCO C3 imagery due to the control arm. High uncertainty of parameters due to limited stereoscopic viewpoints.

note: CME visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. No STEREO A COR2 imagery for this event due to a data gap. The source of this CME may be the M1.2 flare from AR14028 (S17W33) as seen in SDO/AIA 131 and 193. There is clear dimming and moving/opening field lines visible to the SW of the eruption suggesting deflection. This may be due to a coronal hole due north of the source location.

cmeAnalyses.note: Parameters based on best fit using SOHO LASCO C3 imagery and the potential source location. Some uncertainty due to limited stereoscopic viewpoints.

note: Faint CME seen to the north-north-east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and to the north in STEREO A COR2 (along the northern streamer). Its source is the filament eruption seen beyond the north-north-east limb starting ~2025-03-22T07:18Z in SDO AIA 193/171 and GOES SUVI 304/284, with coronal signatures including a large prominence/ejecta (or even double ejecta) in AIA 171, SIVI 304/284 and as faint opening of field lines in AIA 193.

cmeAnalyses.note: Very approximate analysis based on the best fit with two coronagraphs and affected by the poor quality of STEREO A coronagraph imagery because of the ongoing campaign. The source is on the far side.

note: This CME is visible to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. The source is likely related to an eruption near Active Region 14037 (N22W32) starting around 2025-03-22T13:20Z seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the source location.

note: This CME is visible to the north/northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. The source is likely related to an eruption centered near N28E45 starting around 2025-03-22T13:45Z which exhibits northern deflection as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the source location.

note: This CME is visible to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. The source is likely related to an eruption centered near N18E52 starting around 2025-03-22T13:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. Dimming is visible north of the eruption site in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery starting around 2025-03-22T14:00Z and an opening of field lines can be observed over the northeast limb in GOES SUVI 284 imagery at this time. Additionally, post-eruptive arcades begin to form around 2025-03-22T14:30Z in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measured longitude based on the source location. The eruption exhibits northern deflection which may explain the latitude measuring higher than the on-disk source latitude.

note: This CME is faint but visible as a partial halo directed towards the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. It is observed as a faint far-sided halo in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided, and may be related to faint field line movement visible far beyond the southeast limb in GOES SUVI 284 imagery starting around 2025-03-22T14:35Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: SHOCK measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery and the one available frame of this event seen in STEREO A COR2 imagery, due to an ongoing campaign. This event is likely far-sided and the source location is unknown. The measured parameters may vary as a result.

BULK measurement using the same longitude as what was measured in the shock measurement. The measured parameters may vary greatly as the bulk portion of this event is difficult to distinguish in STEREO A COR2 imagery. Additionally, this event is likely far-sided so there is no source location to confirm the measured parameters.

note: Faint, constant outflow of minor fronts to the northeast from approximately 2025-03-23T08:36Z to 2025-03-23T13:25Z, with two of the fronts being more prominent: this one is the earlier of the two, and becomes more discernible in SOHO C3 white light and running difference imagery with time. The two more prominent fronts seem to combine/overlap about halfway into C3's field-of-view around 13Z. No clear source has been found for these outflows.

cmeAnalyses.note: Since the front is not discernible in STEREO A COR2 running difference imagery and there is no clear source for this CME, only plane-of-sky measurement can be made (with SOHO imagery only).

note: Part of the constant outflow of multiple faint flows to the northeast. This front seems to be more eastward-directed compared to previous, more northern 2025-03-23T08:36Z CME/outflow. These two CMEs eventually seem to combine/overlap about halfway into C3's FOV around 13Z. No clear source has been found for this CME.

cmeAnalyses.note: Since the front of this CME is not discernible in STEREO A COR2 running difference imagery and there is no clear source for this CME, only plane-of-sky measurement can be made (with SOHO imagery only).

note: Faint CME seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, and SSE in STEREO COR2A. The source from this CME is uncertain and appears far-sided, via observed field line movement in SDO AIA 171 over the SE limb beginning around 2025-03-23T10:03Z and a triangulated STEREOCAT tool measurement.

cmeAnalyses.note: Triangulated SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO COR2A measurement via the STEREOCAT tool, as STEREO COR2A is currently in campaign mode and its running difference imagery in SWPC_CAT does not resolve the faint CME well.

note: This narrow CME is visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. It is not clearly seen in STEREO A COR2 imagery due to an ongoing campaign. The source appears to be filament ejecta with associated field line movement to the SE in SDO/AIA 171, 193, and 304 starting around 2025-03-24T15:22Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement using swpc_cat measurement technique. Parameters based on best fit in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery.

note: Narrow CME (less than ten degree half-width) first seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 started at 2025-03-24T19:24Z. CME is also seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C3 but is not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap beginning 2025-03-24T16:09Z. The source of this CME is possibly a small amount of ejecta from beyond the SE limb best seen in SDO AIA 304 starting at 2025-03-24T19:06Z. Some very faint field line movement from beyond the SE limb can also be seen in SDO AIA 171 and SDO AIA 193 starting around 2025-03-24T19:04Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement made with running difference imagery from SOHO LASCO C2/C3 using SWPC_CAT. Plane-of-sky measurement chosen due to data gap in STEREO A COR2 and lack of certainty in source location.
